text:
Also, RE: wrestlers and body hair (or hair in general)...Specifically with Spectator/Scripted wresting (I don't know about actual sports/competitive wresting)- long head hair is generally considered to be a no-go zone (much like low blows). 
Wrestlers tend to be smooth-bodied and oiled because of FRICTION. The moves that they perform actually would hurt the skin quite a lot due to the rubbing and chafing. Being smooth helps with that, but anyone who's ever either plucked/waxed or otherwise RIPPED OUT hair (either accidentally or deliberately) will tell you...it freaking hurts. 
It's not that the wrestlers think their opponents might do it on purpose (generally, everything they do is designed to LOOK painful but actually not be damaging), but that...well, as the meme goes...
You can't get your hair ripped out (accidentally or otherwise) if you don't have any hair.

text:
Gura, If your pc feels like it's dying, you should get apps to keep an eye on CPU temperature and GPU temperature.
The CPU should be in the range of 50-70C, and the GPU should be in the range of 60-85C.
Enable V-sync in games will limit the load on the GPU and can help lower GPU temperature.
If your CPU temperature is in the 90C then you should check the cooler is working and has good contact with the CPU surface.
Remember thermal paste. It's really important.
I personally use Core-temp for CPU, and GPU-z for GPU (Sensor pane).
Be aware of extra stuff Core-temp wants to install, just remove the check marks and you are good.
